\ul Some things I have learned\ulnone\par
\par
1. The bigger the database the better.\par
2. Letter searches are not the answer as there are too many combinations and for each lay of a letter you only check for two words of the common letter. So even with a fast calculation time for each letter, all the recursion adds up. Laying a word and checking that all the croossing words will have a possible word, although much slower, has fewer recursive calls. On most test scenerios I had tried, laying words was faster.\par
3. Each time you lay a word, you must ensure that all it's crossing word positions will be able to fit a word. If not, you will preform too many recursions. The code is more complex, but it is worth it.\par
4. Your path algorithm for laying words must ensure that each following word in your path crosses the previous one. This helps with wasted recursions in the case of doing all across words, then checking if the down words are valid.\par
5. Optimal (not naive) backtracks help a lot (x100 speed increases or more in some cases).\par
