Searches\ulnone\par
\par
There are many types of searches we can perform to try and determine what word or letter will fit on our crossword.\par
\par
\b Prefix / Linear Seraches : Return the next potential letters after a given series of letters\par
Note: This was for a letter by letter search and is no longer used.\b0\par
\par
Given the prefix letters for a word, return the next possible letters.\par
eg: given 'boa--' found in the space for a 5 letter word, the next letter might be t or r.\par
This is useful only if you plan to build words from beggining to end. It will not allow for filling in letters in a random order.\par
\par
Method 1. Intitially I built a chain of hash references and required the word length also. This required that we follow, or loop through, the chain of hash references. It was more complex but was still fast. \par
$nextLetter[numberOfLettersInWord] would point to a list of hashes where the keys were possible first letters. So a "keys %nextLetter[5]" would return all the first letters of possible 5 letter words. If we chose the letter 'b', and referenced $nextLetter[5]\{b\} we would get a list of hash references to all the potential 2nd letters of 5 letter words that start with 'b'.\par
\par
\cf2 *Method 2\cf0 . Then I decided that it was simpler to implement and slightly faster to just use masks using prefixes. That would eliminate the need to supply the word length (as the mask is the right length). And no loops throgh a  series of hashes was necessary.\par
$linearWordSearch\{CAo\} returned ( $\{'T'\} , $\{'R'\} , $\{'B'\} , $\{'N'\} )\par
I did not return a list of letters. I return a list of keys. This simplifies the list creation ensuring there are no duplicate letters\par
@letters = keys %\{$linearWordSearch\{$mask\}\};\par
Note: the mask must be a prefix mask only. ie: HIGoooooo\par
It is 1.5 times faster than the old way.\par
Memory storage is about the same.\par
\par
\b Mask Searches : @words = &\cf3 WordsFromMask($mask) $mask = \lquote GOoD\rquote  :  Return a list of potential words for a given mask\cf0\par
\b0\par
Method 1. For a given mask (eg \cf3 GOoD\cf0 ), cycle through all the letters. For each letter return a list (built before hand) of all words, the same length as the mask, that have that letter in that position. Do that for all all letters that we have in the mask. Then we compare all the lists and keep the words that show up in all the lists. \par
It was complex, and was not all that fast as we had to repaetedly compare potentially large lists of words.\par
It's memory use was average to high as a  word string was stored multiple times, at least as many times as letters in the word. Eg DOG was stored 3 times, once for each letter.\par
\par
\cf2 *Method 2\cf0 . Words of Length String. For each word length we have created a large comma delimited string consisting of all the words of that length before hand. We use regular expressions to search that string for the mask and return the list of words.\par
The memory storage is as efficient as one could hope for. eg DOG is only stored once in the comma delimited words of 3 letter string.\par
The speed is surprizingly fast for searching long strings.\par
\par
my $tempMask = $mask;\line $tempMask =~ s/$unoccupied/\\./g; #make a mask of 'GO$unoccupiedT' into 'GO.T' for the regexp\line my $wordLength = length($tempMask);\line @word_list = ($WordsOfLengthString[$wordLength] =~ /($tempMask),/g);\par
\par
Method 3. Binary Mask. For each word we build a binary mask. Then for each mask we create a list of words that belong to that mask.\par
Eg: CAT -> CAT , CAo , CoT , Coo , oAT , etc\par
In theory it should be very fast. But it is only slightly faster than the Words of Length String word search in some cases. \par
Copying or accessing the list takes the majority of the time and therefore is not much faster for cases where the list returned will be large. Small returned lists are faster as the Method 2 still needs to search the complete comma delimited string. \par
So smaller returned word lists will show a speed improvement with this meathod.\par
However, this method uses \b large\b0  amounts of memory as longer words cause exponential memory growth.\par
It also takes a long time to build the database as we need to create many (grows exponentially as the word is longer) binary masks (and associated word lists) for every word in the dictionary. \par
